The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps the entire `System.IO` surface. No custom wrappers needed.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions              # production project
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # test project
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs / Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

The API mirrors `System.IO` exactly — `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)` instead of `File.ReadAllText(...)`, so migration is mechanical.

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

// ReadAllText
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

// WriteAllText
manager.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists
Assert.True(manager.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
Assert.False(manager.EnsureDirectory("/nope"));
```

### Migration summary

| Before (untestable) | After (injectable) |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(p)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(p)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(p, c)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(p, c)` |
| `Directory.Exists(p)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(p)` |

Once you're ready to do the bulk call-site replacement across your codebase, I can help with that too (using the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` workflow).
